title Telecoms Sovereignty — Nation-State Perspective (Oct 2022)
style wardley

// === Anchors — the four stakeholders with a claim on telecoms sovereignty ===
anchor Government [0.98, 0.55]
anchor The Collective (society / civil society) [0.96, 0.40]
anchor Corporations (telcos / OEMs / platforms) [0.94, 0.70]
anchor People (citizens / subscribers) [0.92, 0.80]

// === Sovereignty pillars — what the nation is trying to defend ===
// (positioned high on visibility because they are the outputs the state cares about;
//  evolution varies because some are well-doctrine'd and some are still being defined)
component Territorial Sovereignty [0.90, 0.78]
component Political Sovereignty [0.88, 0.60]
component Cultural Sovereignty [0.86, 0.48]
component Economic Sovereignty [0.84, 0.70]
component Digital Sovereignty [0.82, 0.32]
component CNI Protection (telecoms as CNI) [0.80, 0.55]

// === Access devices — what the citizen holds ===
component Smartphone [0.76, 0.92]
component Personal Computer [0.74, 0.94]
component Radio / TV Receiver [0.72, 0.96]
component Satellite Phone [0.70, 0.55]
component IoT Endpoint [0.68, 0.72]
component SIM / eSIM [0.66, 0.88]

